<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-01-05T12:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-01-05T12:00:00-05:00" n="16" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d16">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 656.119/122</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_PWH1" type="from"><hi rend="italic">Page</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                </hi>
                            </head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                            </opener>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-01-05T17:00:00+00:00">
                                        <hi rend="italic">January 5, 1918, 5 p.m.</hi>
                                    </date>
                                    <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received 11.15 p.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>8161. Following for War Trade Board from <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_SLP1">Sheldon</persName>:</p>
                            <p>No. 3. Referring <persName>Frothingham</persName>’s telegram to War
                                Trade Board, No. 34, December 4.<note n="1" xml:id="d16fn1">Not
                                    printed.</note> I hope early decision will be reached regarding
                                discontinuance or otherwise navicerts as affecting Dutch tonnage to
                                lift their own rations under part [<hi rend="italic">provisional?</hi>] Dutch agreement. Tonnage proposals for
                                ultimate agreement presume continuance of Halifax visits which Dutch
                                seem to object to. While calls at Halifax ought not to be objected
                                to by Dutch and for [<hi rend="italic">under?</hi>] provisional <hi rend="italic">modus operandi</hi>, the question is more serious
                                for tonnage arrangements under definite agreement. If the system of
                                navicerts be not abandoned it should be understood for purposes of
                                American prestige in Holland that system is approved by Allies and
                                not dictated solely by His Majesty’s Government. An early reply will
                                be appreciated.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_PWH1">
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Page</hi>
                                    </persName>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>